main event: An unidentified aircraft was observed over Army Observation Post #1 in South Korea on 14 November 1948, flying east to west at an altitude of 3000 feet. It was also spotted by other observation posts in the area.
interesting points: The aircraft was believed to be a twin-engine bomber and was identified as of Soviet origin.
The incident was documented on a Temporary ATC Form 329 on 4 November 1948.
According to Dr. Hynek's evaluations extracted from Project Grudge report, some incidents had high or fair probability for astronomical explanations while others were not explained.
The report included incident summaries, comments, and recommendations for the investigation of unidentified aerial objects.
Some incidents were suggestive of other explanations such as ordinary aircraft, rockets, flares, falling bodies, and miscellaneous causes like reflections and birds.
witnesses: Army Observation Post #1 and other observation posts
photographs: no photographs included in the report
